post_text:
Welcome to the 1st day of school for the 2020-21 school year! While it is not our 'normal' start, we are anticipating a great time of teaching and learning this year. Our teams have been working hard to prepare and are excited, and probably nervous too, to deliver education in a new way. Thank you in advance for your support, patience, and grace as we launch this new year.

We'd also love to see your back to school photos ... please email to laurie.wiedenmeyer@tumwater.k12.wa.us.

Remember we are all in this together and will come out of it #TumwaterStronger

post_text:
Great news for families! The USDA extended free meals for all children (18 and under) through December 31st. What does this mean?
‚Ä¢ Children will NOT have to pay for school meals.
‚Ä¢ FREE breakfast and lunch will be served to students and community members who are 18 years and younger in a ‚Äògrab and go‚Äô manner.
‚Ä¢ At this point in time, meals will be served on school days only.
‚Ä¢ Child Nutrition guidelines state we must have a signed waiver with the parent signature to pick up meals or the student must be present.
‚Ä¢ Daily Food will be available at each school for pick up from 8-1 each day. Please call if possible to order 5-day meal boxes so we can better plan. 360 709-7741

We are working to identify areas that meals can be delivered to make this more accessible and convenient for families.

https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2020/08/31/usda-extends-free-meals-kids-through-december-31-2020

Suffragettes stopped in Tumwater this morning to celebrate Votes for Women Centennial - Washington State with Mark Twain.

In 1909, Twain told the New York Sun he supported women‚Äôs right to vote for over fifty years. In a letter published in the London Evening Standard in 1874, he wrote "I've been persuaded that in extending the suffrage to women this country could lose absolutely nothing and might gain a great deal."

post_text:
The District is currently hosting a Zoom informational session on Tumwater Virtual Academy (TVA). The session is at capacity and unable to take on any more viewers.

The Student Learning Department is recording the session and will ensure that it is available to families and students as soon as possible.

We apologize for the inconvenience. We know families have a lot of interest and questions about TVA. You can be certain that the District will continue to communicate information regarding this opportunity. In addition to the recording of the Zoom session we are currently working on a Frequently Asked Questions page of our website.

Thank you for your understanding and patience!

As we make plans to bring students back to school in the fall, it is imperative that we hear from our families. If you haven't already, please take a moment to take our survey before it closes on June 29th at 6 pm. This is the first survey in which we are asking general overarching questions. In the next week or two, additional input will be requested that will provide opportunity to give more detailed information and share thoughts, ideas, concerns, preferences, limitations, and more.

Thank you Tumwater SD families for participating! Follow this link if you haven't already taken the survey: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSer5VsddQOM95bVboyebqczgyi42j3J48WdvpAROt6YVmkrdQ/viewform

We continue to honor our Class of 2020 seniors during this time of extended school closure. Posts are published in the order they are received. Send your senior information today!

Today we honor Jessica Villarreal - Black Hills High School Class of 2020! Jessica was inspired to become a teacher by her first school teacher, Mrs. Birindell, and also through working in a daycare. At BHHS, she completed all of her volunteer hours with her favorite English teacher, Mrs. Fulton. During that time, she was able to see first-hand what it is like to be a teacher and that helped confirm to her teaching is her dream job. Jessica has participated in school choirs since elementary school. Her last two years she performed in Con Brio. Jessica plans to attend South Puget Sound Community College and then Western Washington University to earn a Bachelors in Early Childhood Education. She hopes to teach 1st or 2nd grade in the future. Congratulations Jessica!

We continue to honor our Class of 2020 seniors during this time of extended school closure. Posts are published in the order they are received. Send your senior information today!

Today we honor Tyler Thompson - Tumwater High School Class of 2020! Tyler has been attending Running Start full time for the past two years and will graduate with Honors and an Associate of Arts degree. Tyler earned the all-academic award each year of high school, varsity lettered three years and won MVP this last season of golf. He also qualified to go to State (which unfortunately was cancelled). Tyler enjoyed playing tenor saxophone all four years for the zero hour jazz band, earning first chair this past year. In all, he was offered over $120,000 in academic scholarships. Tyler will attend Washington State University this fall to pursue the Architecture Studies program. Congratulations Tyler!

Today we honor Lea Prandi - Black Hills High School Class of 2020! Lea spent the last two years of high school as a Running Start student and will graduate with her high school diploma and her Associate of Arts degree from SPSCC. Lea recently returned from a short-term mission trip to Guatemala where she served in a home for kids with special needs. Way to go Lea!

Way to go Lea!

Today we honor Matthew Miller - Tumwater High School and New Market F.I.T.E. Class of 2020! At the age of three, Matthew began his time in Tumwater schools. While trying to find his niche in learning, enrolling in the F.I.T.E. class at New Market has helped him find that and is happy to boast A's and B's. His heart to help others coupled with the F.I.T.E. program helped him realize his future career as a First Responder - Firefighter/EMT. At the end of his junior year, he was voted by his F.I.T.E. peers as the "Junior Class Rookie of the Year". Last December, he participated in the Wildland Fire Incident Qualification and earned his "red card" which will enable him to fight forest fires once he graduates. He is also able to boast perfect attendance this year - until the buildings closed. He has taken great pride in his attendance all through his high school career. Way to go, Matthew!

Today's honors go to Tumwater High School Class of 2020 - Abbey Ryle! Abbey is an accomplished student, both academically and musically. She holds a 3.92 GPA and was appointed Concert Master with the orchestra her senior year. She was also part of a string quartet and performed at special events. Outside of school, she has performed Irish fiddle music around the community. She has also enjoyed her time participating in the THS Cultural Awareness Club. She will attend Oregon State University as part of their Honor's College, pursuing degrees in Zoology/Biology and Nutrition. Abbey's volunteer experience includes time at the Olympia Police Department, Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife, and is currently an Ambassador for the Arthritis Foundation, supporting young people with arthritis and autoimmune diseases. Congratulations Abbey!

Here's another example from one of our fabulous teachers demonstrating creativity to bring learning opportunities from a distance:

Each year, Peter G. Schmidt teacher Erin Crabtree's 4th graders read the book "Some Kind of Courage" by Washington state author Dan Gemeinhart and then the students would have an opportunity to Skype with him. This year, he agreed to a Zoom meeting which gave students an opportunity to "meet the author" then ask questions about his book and the writing process. She then hopes to transfer to a university and earn a BA. Congratulations Estrella!

post_text:
The state recently recognized four Tumwater School District schools for growth, closing achievement gaps, and demonstrated achievement in specific areas during the 2018-19 school year.

We celebrate and congratulate the staff and students at:

East Olympia Elementary - growth for students who receive special education services
Michael T. Simmons Elementary - growth for students identifying as Asian
Tumwater Hill Elementary - closing gaps for one or more student groups at a targeted support school
Tumwater Middle School - growth for students identifying as Black and students who are English learners

Tumwater‚Äôs Superintendent, Dr. Sean Dotson, states, ‚ÄúWe are thankful for the ongoing commitment and hard work of our staff, teachers, and students that have resulted in these honors. Our staff continue to work together with a focus on helping all students grow. It is exciting to see Tumwater‚Äôs commitment to improving educational equity is making a difference.‚Äù

Meet Julion Mack - Tumwater High School Class of 2020! Julion has maintained a GPA of 3.5 while taking rigorous classes, including AP, throughout high school. He was invited to go on an honors class trip to Paris, Germany and The Alps, but due to the pandemic the trip was canceled. He holds his head high reflecting on all of his accomplishments so far. During the school closures, he has continued working as an essential worker. Julion is part of the Delayed Entry Program for the United States Air Force and will attend BMT training in mid-July. After training, Julion will attend Embry-Riddle where he will continue his education as an Aerospace Engineer while serving in the United States Air Force. Congratulations Julion!

Today we honor THS Senior Savannah Owen! Savannah is an active member of Renaissance Club and for the last two years has been assisting with the Life Skills class. She shares that helping out in this class has changed her outlook on life. So much so that she will continue her education in the fall at Saint Martin's University on a softball scholarship and will study special education. During high school she attended the Student Equity Summit, bringing her ideas of how to ensure all kids matter. Along with her activities, she played four years on varsity softball with two trips to the state tournament and participated in Cross Country her freshman year with a trip to compete at the State meet. During off-season, Savannah is employed as a hostess at Emperor's Palace. Way to go!

Today we honor THS Class of 2020 Atticus Zambrana! Atticus was involved in the robotics club where he was first introduced to coding. He took advanced classes on making and flying drones, writing code for video games, and cyber security during summer courses offered at New Market Skills Center. He has been active in Technology Student Association (TSA) and was co-leader of the team that developed an original video game then competed at the state level. During the health pandemic, he has been busy serving our community by being an essential grocery delivery person. This fall, Atticus will attend Bates Technical College to earn an Associate of Applied Science degree in the field of cyber security. Way to go!

Today we highlight Sophie O'Brien - Black Hills High School Class of 2020! While Sophie has accomplished much worthy of celebration during her high school years, we are celebrating her in this current moment. Sophie is an essential employee during the pandemic and has continued to work since the outbreak of COVID-19. She has covered and taken on extra shifts to pay for her own car and is excited to get her own apartment in June. Amidst the pandemic, she has put herself at risk for exposure by going to work every day while providing exceptional customer service to all those she greets. After high school, Sophie will be pursuing a degree in social work to become a child protective services investigator.

Honoring our awesome Class of 2020 seniors:

Cameron Collins will graduate from Tumwater High School this year. Just this week Cameron received the news that he was accepted at Embry-Riddle in Arizona where he plans to study Aerospace Engineering and will be joining the ROTC, Air Force branch. Cameron has attended Tumwater schools since he was a peer model in preschool. In high school, he has enjoyed being part of Leadership and the THS News. He has served over 600 volunteer hours in the past four years for programs such as Stuff the Bus, Project Prom, Holiday Assistance Program, and more. Cameron also works for the B&G Club in Tumwater.

post_text:
Honoring our awesome Class of 2020!

Meet Layne Fry - Tumwater High School Class of 2020. Layne is the president of the THS Thespian Troupe, and has been accepted to Lewis & Clark, Western Washington University, and the University of Evansville, Indiana. She was invited to interview for the Theater Management Program at UofE after being selected for a callback audition during high school auditions. After spending a weekend immersed in UofE's theater program and being interviewed, Layne was one of three students accepted into the Theater Management program - along with a generous scholarship offer. Layne is spending some time evaluating her options before committing.

When the kids in our life are struggling, they often express it through their behavior rather than their words. You may have seen some of those behaviors already: irritability, change in sleeping and eating patterns, forgetfulness, etc. Take a look at these ideas - shared by Mary Bridge Children's Hospital - on how you can help the kids in your life make their way through a time filled with uncertainty and even fear.

Reactions in children with special needs will likely be based on the child‚Äôs developmental level. Most of the behaviors should respond to the strategies listed below.

Learn more at https://www.marybridge.org/coronavirus/

#WeGotThisTacoma

post_text: Important information re: Boys & Girls Club registration during the closure. Please take a moment to read this if you plan to register. Also, keep in mind that this should be for those who have no other viable option for care. Thank you!
shared_text:
Tumwater Boys & Girls Club
March 15 at 3:09 PM ¬∑

Club Families:
The registration process on Wednesday morning will be as follows:
We will send parents of current members with a short registration form for this All Day Camp. The form can be returned at pick up.
New members:
If capacity allows, the only new members who will be registered are those who are children of First Responders/Medical Professionals. New member registration requires full paperwork Wednesday morning, please allow time for this.
There is a fee for All Day Camp as we do need to cover costs the Club incurs for the extended hours of operation. The fee will be $85 per week per child, as always we have scholarships available to those who qualify. We will work with all families who need payment plans. Families who have made any payments for March will recieve a partial credit toward any balance incurred for the All Day Camp.
Space is limited as we need to practice as much social distancing as possible.
We ask that families only use the Club out of necessity.

Meet the 2020 Capital Lakefair Queen ... Black Hills HS Junior Makenna Beeson!

At a coronation ceremony this past weekend, Makenna was chosen to represent our area in appearances through the PNW at various festivals and community events. She will also volunteer over 300 hours this next year in her role as Queen. Chosen from a quality group of individuals, Makenna was the winner after being judged on an essay entry, speaking ability, confidence, reaction under pressure, and much more. The Capital Lakefair Royalty Program is a scholarship program that honors the outstanding achievements and leadership of young women in our community. The last Lakefair from Tumwater School District was in 2007.

Congratulations Makenna!
BHHS Capital Lakefair

post_text:
Over the years, our Tumwater community has consistently supported education funding measures that put our students first and provide them with a world class education. Whether a Capital Bond that funded building improvements, or an Educational Programs & Operations levy that covered operational costs not covered by the state funding we receive, Tumwater citizens value education and the students of our community! See our website for more information about the replacement EP&O and Capital Levy ballot measures. https://www.tumwater.k12.wa.us/Page/7509
#EducationLevies2020

post_text: Congratulations BHHS senior Lily Campbell for being named YWCA Olympia's 2019 Young Womxn of Achievement! She is being honored at an event next weekend for her work launching the Girls Outreach Club at BHHS, with the goals to empower women, develop a safe space for conversations, and create a sense of wellness and support. She and co-leader Ainsley Campbell wrote and presented a grant to United Women of Thurston County as 9th graders, where they received the funds to support their club. Their annual hygiene product drives have raised over $1,000 worth of donations for the Other Bank. She also runs a mentoring program called Girl Talk at Tumwater Middle School. What an inspiration! YWCA of Olympia The Olympian ThurstonTalk.com

shared_text:
Thurston Co. Scanner, News, & Weather Blog
October 21, 2019 at 1:12 PM ¬∑

4 semi truck accident near Maytown milepost 96 on I-5 southbound. Both directions blocked by semi trucks. Multiple injuries reported. Airlift is being put on standby. Please avoid I-5 in this area.

There are 3 patients at this time. Initial reports were one serious, two minor injuries.
WSP is closing down southbound I5 at 93rd Ave.
Tow is being requested for 3 semi's. Also a 4th semi is off the road but doesn't appear to need tow.

All patients are being transported to St. Petes.

WSP has confirmed there are no serious injuries.

If anyone has taken any photos of this accident, please feel free to message them to us with permission to use.

We are so proud of our own Erin Novak for starting a pilot Spanish program with EOE 1st and 2nd graders. The end of year fiesta was Thursday night and it was obvious this program was a success. Erin is fluent in Spanish and American Sign Language and taught the kids many songs to perform in both languages. The children passed along their love for the cultures they‚Äôve been leaning about and shared food from Spanish speaking countries.

We were honored to have State Superintendent of Public Instruction Chris Reykdal come for the festivities along with two Tumwater School Board members, Kim Reykdal and Khalia Davis.

post_text:
Tumwater Hill Elementary families,

The school and surrounding areas have experienced a power outage and at this time, Puget Sound Energy has not estimated a time it will be restored. As a result, we will be dismissing school today at 11:30. If parents want to pick their students up prior to that, you are welcome to do so. For bus riders, please know that students will not be dropped at their stop without an adult to meet them. If a student doesn't have an adult at their stop, they will ride the bus back to the school and a bus will run at the end of the day after our normal release time. We will transport Boys & Girls Club students to the Club. If they are unable to open early, they will ride back to the school and go back at the normal time. Y-Care on our campus has been cancelled for the afternoon. We apologize for the inconvenience this causes.

post_text: Each of these wonderful TSD teachers and staff members will retire at the end of the school year! At our recent TSD Retirement Celebration, these and a few others were honored for their collective 400+ years of dedication, caring, and commitment to students and education. While each of them will be missed, we are excited for them as they start their next chapter. Congratulations 2018-19 retirees!

post_text: The FRESH program currently has 12 spots available for upcoming sophomores, juniors, and seniors who are looking for alternative academic pathways. This full year/5 credit academic program builds skills in teamwork, sustainable agriculture, personal empowerment, and community engagement. We are accepting applications now for our 7 week summer program. During this time, students work together to run a small farm at Isabella Bush Park on Linwood Avenue in Tumwater. The farm provides fresh vegetables for the Tumwater Senior Center and TOGETHER! Resource Centers. Students earn an education stipend of up to $1000 and 1 elective credit for the 7 week summer program. If you would like to apply please visit the THS or BHHS counseling offices for an application. Please pass this information on to those you think would be interested.
